# =============================================================================
# geometry/2D_random_bumpy_floor_molaroscale.opts — the bumpy-floor-with-ice-
# caps domain (2D_random_bumpy_floor.opts) rescaled so the largest ice grain
# matches the Molaro grains, and re-meshed on the LOOSE eps criteria.
#
# WHAT CHANGED vs 2D_random_bumpy_floor.opts
# -------------------------------------------
# Uniform geometric scaling by s = 6.7335 = 1.01e-4 / 1.5e-5, i.e. the old
# largest ice grain (R = 1.5e-5, right boundary) is blown up to the Molaro
# large-grain radius R = 1.0100e-4. EVERYTHING scales by the same s:
#
#   Lx  2.0e-4  -> 1.3467e-3        Ly  4.0e-5  -> 2.6933e-4
#   bump R-range  5.0-7.0e-6  -> 3.3667e-5 - 4.7133e-5
#   ice grains    R 3.0e-6-1.5e-5 -> 2.0200e-5 - 1.0100e-4
#
# WHY UNIFORM (and not "scale the ice grains only"): MAX_SED_GRAINS = 24
# (NASA_types.h). The original design covers the whole floor with exactly 24
# bumps, no flat gaps. A 6.7x wider floor at the ORIGINAL bump size would need
# ~162 bumps -- silently truncated at 24 by the C code, leaving most of the
# floor flat. Scaling the bumps with the domain keeps the 24-bump full coverage
# and preserves the tuned overlap/clearance design (critical overlap ~0.36).
#
# The scaled layout is geometrically similar to the original: same seed=0, same
# dimensionless height-ratio (0.15-0.28) and overlap (0.20-0.32) ranges, so the
# bump list is the old one times s to 2.7e-5 relative (that residual is just
# the rounding of Lx to 1.3467e-3). Generation-time check reports max height
# 4.7% of Ly -- IDENTICAL to the original's 4.7% -- and max curvature 1.495e5,
# 7x LOWER than the original's ~1.0e6 (bigger bumps are gentler).
#
# MESH: the loose criteria validated on 2026-07-15
# ------------------------------------------------
#   eps = 8.5840e-7  (K&P via comp_eps.py at -20 C, alpha_c = 1.341e-2; the
#   D*_ia heat channel with B-KINETIC binding). The union-IC eps series
#   (batch_2026-07-15__15.31.58_epsunion) showed this eps reproduces the
#   3.479e-7 "strict" mesh to 0.7% on neck width at t=120 min, at 1/6 the
#   nodes -- which is what makes THIS domain affordable:
#       loose  eps=8.584e-7 -> 2219 x 444  = 0.99M nodes   <- THIS FILE
#       strict eps=3.479e-7 -> 5475 x 1095 = 6.00M nodes
#   h = eps/sqrt(2) (the current convention; NOTE the original bumpy-floor
#   geometry predates it and used h ~ eps, so do not copy its Nx/Ny scaling).
#
#   eps/R_smallest_cap = 4.2% -- inside comp_eps.py's < 5% guideline, but it is
#   the binding geometric constraint here. The 2.020e-5 floor caps are the
#   least-resolved feature; if they misbehave, that ratio is the first suspect.
#
# Regenerate the mesh with:
#   ./venv_pf311/bin/python3 preprocess/build_geometry_multi_grain.py \
#       --random-bumps --seed 0 --n-bumps 24 \
#       --R-range 3.3667e-5 4.7133e-5 --height-ratio-range 0.15 0.28 \
#       --overlap-range 0.20 0.32 \
#       --Lx 1.3467e-3 --Ly 2.6933e-4 --Nx 2219 --Ny 444 --P 2 --C 1 \
#       --out inputs/geometry/random_bumpy_floor_molaroscale.dat \
#       --variant random_bumpy_floor_molaroscale \
#       --opts inputs/geometry/2D_random_bumpy_floor.opts
#
# INHERITED FAILURE MODES (both from the ORIGINAL scale; see ACTIVITY_LOG
# 2026-06-18/19). Small caps fully sublimating by Ostwald ripening made the AC
# reaction term singular -> SNES failure (job64406550, needed -dtmax capped and
# -max_rej raised) and later a dt limit cycle (job64410270). Scaling UP should
# ease both: the smallest cap is now 2.020e-5, not 3.0e-6, so it takes far
# longer to vanish. The solver.opts guards remain in place regardless.
#
# TIMESCALE WARNING: evaporation-condensation neck growth goes as x^3 = 6*d0*R*t/beta,
# so at FIXED x/R the time to reach a given relative state scales as R^2. This
# geometry is 6.73x larger => ~45x SLOWER in relative terms than the original.
# A 30-day run here shows roughly what 16 hours showed at the old scale. Size
# -t_final accordingly; do not copy the old 30day durations expecting the same
# evolution.
#
# Ice grains (22, all circles): 0 = left boundary, 1 = right boundary (the
# Molaro-sized one, R = 1.0100e-4), 3 and 5 floating mid-channel, the rest
# floor-touching caps (cy = 0). See 2D_random_bumpy_floor.opts for the original
# placement rationale.
# =============================================================================
# DOF_GRID: 2221 446
-geom_file inputs/geometry/random_bumpy_floor_molaroscale.dat
-p 2
-C 1
-ic_type multi_grains
-dim 2
-Lx 1.3467e-3
-Ly 2.6933e-4
-Lz 0
-sed_grain_x 0.000000e+00,6.118530e-05,1.149549e-04,1.761537e-04,2.379108e-04,2.905014e-04,3.504690e-04,4.160697e-04,4.703547e-04,5.185766e-04,5.707491e-04,6.281199e-04,6.886801e-04,7.451799e-04,8.130173e-04,8.713148e-04,9.286215e-04,9.819187e-04,1.038499e-03,1.095012e-03,1.150296e-03,1.216467e-03,1.283329e-03,1.346700e-03
